[1] China (Hong Kong)
Date: Tue, 7 Oct 2003 06:48:33 -0700 (PDT)
From: Alan Wu <alanklwu@yahoo.com>
Source: HK Dept of Health 7 Oct 2003, press release [edited]
<http://www.dh.gov.hk/>

Locally acquired dengue fever - Hong Kong
----------------------------------------
The Department of Health (DH) and the Food & Environmental
Hygiene Department (FEHD) today (7 Oct 2003) urged members
of the public to take vigorous preventive measures against
mosquito breeding following the confirmation of the first local case
of dengue fever this year [2003].
Speaking at a press conference this afternoon, Consultant
(Community Medicine) of DH's Disease Prevention and Control
Division, Dr Thomas Tsang, said the case involved a 26-year-old
man who had onset of disease on 27 Sep 2003. Clinical symptoms
included fever, headache, muscle pain, and skin rash.
The patient consulted a private doctor on 30 Sep 2003 and was
admitted to Yan Chai Hospital on 2 Oct 2003. Blood test taken at
Yan Chai Hospital was subsequently confirmed positive for dengue
fever by DH's Public Health Laboratory Center. The patient is now
convalescing at home.
"As the patient had not traveled outside Hong Kong during the
incubation period which lasts from 3 to 14 days, this has been
classified as a confirmed local case. The patient's family and
workplace contacts who have been traced by DH are found to be
asymptomatic. However, as a precautionary measure, we have put
them under close medical surveillance," Dr Tsang said.
As part of the preventive measures, staff of DH and FEHD visited
the patient's residence in Yuen Kong Village, Yuen Long, as well as
his workplace at Kwai Chung Container Terminal today for
epidemiological survey and comprehensive mosquito control action.
The DH has set up a special hotline 2961 8966 for case finding,
health advice\, and counseling. Persons who had stayed or visited
Yuen Kong Village in Yuen Long and Kwai Chung Container
Terminal on or after 15 Aug 2003 and who developed dengue fever
symptoms within 14 days afterwards after the visit are advised to
call the special hotline. Dengue fever symptoms may include fever,
headache, muscle pain, and skin rashes. The hotline is manned by
health nurses and it starts operation this afternoon until 9 pm today.
It will be manned from 9am to 5 pm from tomorrow onward until
further notice.
Anti-mosquito messages in multiple languages, including Japanese,
Filipino, Indonesian, Thai, Sri Lankan, Nepali, and Pakistani were
uploaded onto the FEHD's website <http://www.fehd.gov.hk> to
ensure that minority groups were taken care of in the dengue
prevention programme.
Information on dengue fever is available at DH website
<http://www.dh.gov.hk/> and information on mosquito control at
FEHD website <http://www.fehd.gov.hk/>. Members of the public
can also call the hotline of DH's Central Health Education Unit
2833 0111 to obtain health advice on the disease.
A total of 42 confirmed cases of dengue fever has been reported in
Hong Kong so far in 2003. Of these, 41 were imported cases and
one [is this] local case.
--
Dr. Alan Ka-lun Wu
Medical Officer
Division of Infectious Disease,
Department of Medicine and Therapeutics
Prince of Wales Hospital
Hong Kong
<alanklwu@yahoo.com>
[Dengue vector mosquitoes have been caught flying out of
containers opened in North Australia coming from dengue-endemic
East Timor, and found in the USA in a container from China (see
ProMED post "Mosquito transport in goods shipments,"
20021008.5502. So the case's employment at the Container
Terminal may have resulted in his infection by an imported,
container-borne mosquito -- although a report from another source
submitted by Dan Silver states that the case reported being bitten
at home. - Mod.JW]
