[5] Philippines
Date: 6 Oct 2003
From: ProMED <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Manila Bulletin 6 Oct 2003 [edited]
<http://www.mb.com.ph/>

Acting City Mayor Nilo G. Abellera has expressed alarm over the
increasing number of dengue cases in Davao city. Abellera cited
reports from the Regional Epidemiology Surveillance Unit (RESU),
which monitored 1986 dengue fever cases in the region. The
number reflects an increase of 52 percent in cases compared to
the same period last year [2002]. "This is very alarming, the public
should be aware, not only of the disease but also of the many ways
it can be avoided by practicing cleanliness in our surroundings," he
said.
Talomo district recorded 341 dengue cases followed by Buhangin,
314; Poblacion, 195; Toril, 169; Agdao, 130; Bunawan, 106;
Calinan, 34; Baguio, 7 ; & Paquibato with 5 dengue cases
recorded by DOH XI.
In Cebu, the Department of Health in Region 7 recorded some 327
new cases of dengue fever, as it expressed alarm over the
clustering of new cases in the municipalities across Cebu province.
Records of the Regional Epidemiology and Surveillance Unit
(RESU) showed that municipalities that had fewer than 3 dengue
cases in the past months had 10 to 13 cases in September [2003].
Municipalities that have more than 10 or more new cases in
September alone include Bogo, Carcar, Daanbantayan, Minglanilla,
and Naga.
The 327 new cases from 1 Sep -1 Oct 2003 bring to 2120 the total
number of dengue cases so far in 2003, 32 of which have resulted
in deaths. RESU recorded a total of 171 cases between 13 Jul and
10 Aug this year [2003]. For September [2003] alone, 4 deaths
were recorded in Cebu Province. Cebu City also recorded a total
of 11 deaths so far this year [2003].
The number in the municipalities has been increasing and had
already exceeded the 1805 total number of cases recorded in
2002. With the increasing trend in the number of cases in the past
months, [Anofficial] warned that a worse scenario could be
expected in the last quarter of 2003. He said, though, that even if
dengue cases continue to increase, the figures are still within the
expected range and have not yet reached the number recorded in
1998, where the whole province experienced an outbreak of the
disease.
Cebu City recorded the highest number of cases for the month of
September [2003] with a total of 94 cases, Mandaue City ranked
second with 37, followed by Talisay City with 31 & Toledo City
with 14 cases.
Municipalities that have been identified to have a clustering of
cases last month are Barili (3 new cases), Bogo (13), Carmen (4),
Catmon (4), Consolacion (3), Daanbantayan (10), Liloan (5),
Minglanilla (10), Naga (10), San Fernando (4), and Tuburan (4).
