[7] India (New Delhi)
Date: 6 Oct 2003
From: ProMED <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Hindu 7 Oct 2003 [edited]
<http://www.hinduonnet.com/>

Municipal Councillors today expressed concern over the increasing
dengue cases in the Capital and called upon the authorities to
intensify their anti-dengue campaign. Though nearly 400 dengue
cases have been reported from across the city [up from 130 on 24
Sep 2003 -- see ref. (38) below], no confirmed dengue deaths
have occurred, the Municipal Commissioner, Rakesh Mehta, said
at the MCD House meeting here. Of the total number of reported
cases, more than 80 are [imported] from neighbouring States, he
said.
[But] the [opposition] BJP Councillor from Shalimar Bagh, Ram
Kishan Singhal, claimed "In Maharaja Agrasen hospital alone,
there are at least 50 dengue patients admitted. Recently a 28-year-
old man died in Chandni Chowk due to dengue."
******
[8] India (Gujarat)
Date: 6 Oct 2003
From: ProMED <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Times of India 4 Oct 2003 [edited]
<http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/>

With the death of a 10-year-old girl on Wednesday night, dengue
fever claimed its 6th victim in the last [2 weeks]. The young resident
of Savli breathed her last at the KG Patel Children's Hospital in
Vadodara, which has so far reported 32 cases of dengue.
In the wake of the high mortality and increase in number of dengue
cases in the district, the hospital has now [requested that] the
health department at Gandhinagar take stock of the situation. Out of
the 6 deaths reported so far, the youngest victim is a 6-month-old
child, a resident of Salatwada. The other deceased have been
identified as a 5-year-old from Navayard, a 4-year-old and a
5-year-old from Karjan, and a 2-year-old from Subhanpura.
The doctors in the city have been referring the cases to KG Patel
Children's Hospital, as it has 2 ICUs with a capacity to
accommodate 24 patients at a time. "So far, 32 cases have been
admitted, out of which 17 have been discharged and the remaining
are recovering. We have 10 resident doctors and 8 consulting
experts, who are monitoring the patients at our ICU," says medical
superintendent of KG Patel Children's Hospital, Dr Nirupa Munshi.
"Elimination of the breeding sites of the _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito
is the only feasible solution as of now," says Munshi. "It is perhaps
the second time since 1998 that Vadodara has been affected with
dengue. Though the disease is common in coastal areas like Surat,
Vadodara never had it in such great proportions," asserts Munshi.
The high mortality rate has also put the doctors on high alert, even
as patients are pouring in from Godhra, Savli, and Karjan, apart
from city areas in Vadodara.
Says Dr Hitesh Desai, one of the consultants, "The condition of
most patients seems to deteriorate on the 4th and 5th day after
admission, as they suffer massive uncontrolled bleeding from their
nose and mouth. It is a highly unpredictable disease as there is no
definite cure. Only symptomatic treatment [can] help."
******
[9] India (Uttar Pradesh)
Date: 6 Oct 2003
From: ProMED <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Hindustan Times 7 Oct 2003 [edited]
<http://www.hindustantimes.com/>

The number of dengue patients is increasing daily. In Ghaziabad
district, the figure has already gone up to 29, among them 9 cases
reported from Ghaziabad city.
Prominent pathologist Dr Gopesh Aggarwal of Ghaziabad says that
more than 30 patients suffering from high fever are coming to his
lab every day for blood tests and for most of them, the platelet
counts are very low.
